# Verify the help output for the lsp command. The lsp command uses
# the same cobra command handling as every other cue command, so its
# own flags appear in the help output and in shell completion
# suggestions, alongside the inherited root flags.

exec cue help lsp
cmp stdout expect-stdout

exec cue __complete lsp -
cmp stdout expect-complete-stdout

-- expect-stdout --
lsp runs a CUE language server.

The server communicates using the Language Server Protocol (LSP), with
JSONRPC2 over stdin and stdout, and is intended to be run as a child
process of an editor. Running "cue lsp" with no subcommand is
equivalent to running "cue lsp serve".

By default, the server serves a single editor session over stdin and
stdout. It can instead run as a shared daemon serving several editors:
start the daemon with --listen, and configure each editor to run
"cue lsp --remote" to connect to it. With --remote=auto, an editor's
"cue lsp" starts the daemon automatically if it is not already
running.

Usage:
  cue lsp [flags]
  cue lsp [command]

Available Commands:
  serve       run a CUE language server

Flags:
      --extconfig string                 path to config file for external validators
      --extprofile string                profile name for external validators
      --listen string                    run as a daemon, listening on this address. If prefixed by 'unix;', the subsequent address is assumed to be a unix domain socket. Otherwise, TCP is used.
      --listen-timeout duration          when used with --listen, shut down the server when there are no connected clients for this duration
      --remote string                    forward the connection to a remote server at this address. With no special prefix, this is assumed to be a TCP address. If prefixed by 'unix;', the subsequent address is assumed to be a unix domain socket. If 'auto', or prefixed by 'auto;', the remote address is automatically resolved based on the executing environment.
      --remote-listen-timeout duration   when used with --remote=auto, the --listen-timeout value used to start the daemon (default 1m0s)

Global Flags:
  -E, --all-errors     print all available errors
  -C, --chdir string   change working directory before running command (must be the first flag)
  -i, --ignore         proceed in the presence of errors
  -s, --simplify       simplify output

Use "cue lsp [command] --help" for more information about a command.
-- expect-complete-stdout --
--all-errors	print all available errors
-E	print all available errors
--chdir	change working directory before running command (must be the first flag)
-C	change working directory before running command (must be the first flag)
--ignore	proceed in the presence of errors
-i	proceed in the presence of errors
--simplify	simplify output
-s	simplify output
--extconfig	path to config file for external validators
--extprofile	profile name for external validators
--help	help for lsp
-h	help for lsp
--listen	run as a daemon, listening on this address. If prefixed by 'unix;', the subsequent address is assumed to be a unix domain socket. Otherwise, TCP is used.
--listen-timeout	when used with --listen, shut down the server when there are no connected clients for this duration
--remote	forward the connection to a remote server at this address. With no special prefix, this is assumed to be a TCP address. If prefixed by 'unix;', the subsequent address is assumed to be a unix domain socket. If 'auto', or prefixed by 'auto;', the remote address is automatically resolved based on the executing environment.
--remote-listen-timeout	when used with --remote=auto, the --listen-timeout value used to start the daemon
:4
